# AI Assistant Rules

## Philosophy
- Minimalism. Simple is better. KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid).
- Clean code, easy to read, easy to delete.
- Functional Programming — pure functions, immutability, no side effects.
- MVP mindset — deliver the smallest thing that works, then iterate.

## Security Rules (CRITICAL — no exceptions)
- NEVER output or request .env and example.env file contents
- NEVER hardcode API credentials, secret tokens, private keys or passwords in source code
- NEVER send sensitive data to external AI services
- Follow `.aiignore` and `.gitignore` for excluded files — do not read or reference them
- When asking for help, sanitize data (replace real IDs, emails, tokens with placeholders)
- Do not log sensitive information

## Coding Standards
- No semicolons
- No unused variable
- camelCase for variables and functions
- Single quotes for strings
- 2 spaces for indentation
- Always use ESM syntax (import/export)
- Arrow functions preferred, max 3 parameters
- No generator function
- No class and OOP stuff
- Functional programming paradigm (pure functions, immutability)
- Add JSDocs comments before functions and important variables
- Comments must be in American English
- Never use Vietnamese or Chinese in source code
- Respect `eslint.config.js` — do not suggest rule changes

## When Writing Code
- Read existing patterns in the codebase first
- Follow current coding style — do not introduce new patterns unilaterally
- Handle errors explicitly — never swallow errors silently
- Keep dependencies minimal — question every new package

## Testing Standards
- Write tests for critical business logic, all error cases
- Use simple test runners (node:test, bun:test, vitest)
- No complex mocking frameworks unless necessary
- Tests live alongside source: `[module].test.js` next to `[module].js`

## When in Doubt
- Ask for clarification before generating code
- State your assumption explicitly if proceeding without confirmation
- Prefer doing less and asking over doing more and guessing

## Tech Stack
- Runtime: Node.js, Bun, Deno, Browser
- Language: JavaScript with JSDocs (No TypeScript)

### Agent Skills References

Reference these URLs when working on related topics:

- Hono: https://hono.dev/llms-full.txt
- Bun: https://bun.sh/llms-full.txt
- Redis: https://redis.io/llms.txt
- Meilisearch: https://www.meilisearch.com/llms-full.txt

## Context Management

### Purpose
Capture problem-solving state when work is interrupted or handed off between AI agents.
Only used when:
- Problem cannot be completed in one session
- Work is interrupted by higher priority tasks
- Switching between AI agents (e.g., Gemini → Qwen)
- Complex problem requires thinking state preservation

### Storage Location
- All session files stored in `.sessions/` folder at project root

### File Naming Convention
- Format: `YYYYMMDD_HHMM.md` (24-hour format, use UTC timezone)
- Example: `20260317_0750.md` (Saved at 2026-03-17T07:50:00.184Z)

### When to Save
Save context ONLY when user explicitly requests:
- "Save context"
- "Save session"
- "End session"
- "Checkpoint"
- "Handoff to [agent name]"

Do NOT save automatically. User must initiate.

### Problem Solving Flow
Each session file should capture state within these steps:
1. ISSUE IDENTIFIED
2. SOLUTION DISCUSSION
3. SOLUTION DECIDED
4. IMPLEMENTATION
5. TEST
6. REVIEW
7. DEPLOYMENT
8. ISSUE RESOLVED

### Session File Template

Each session file must follow this structure:

```md
# Session Context

## Metadata
- Saved: YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM
- Issue: [Link to Git issue or brief description]
- Phase: [1-Issue | 2-Discussion | 3-Decided | 4-Implementation | 5-Test | 6-Review | 7-Deployment | 8-Resolved]

## Problem Statement
[What problem are we solving? Why does it matter?]

## Current State
[Where are we in the problem solving flow?]

## Explored Solutions
| Solution | Pros | Cons | Status |
|----------|------|------|--------|
| [Option A] | [Pros] | [Cons] | [Accepted | Rejected | Pending] |
| [Option B] | [Pros] | [Cons] | [Accepted | Rejected | Pending] |

## Decisions Made
- [Decision 1] — Rationale: [Why]
- [Decision 2] — Rationale: [Why]

## Pending Questions
- [ ] [Question 1] — Blocked by: [What/Who]
- [ ] [Question 2] — Blocked by: [What/Who]

## Unresolved Thinking
[What was being considered but not yet decided? This is critical for handoff.]

## Completed Work
- [ ] [Item 1]
- [ ] [Item 2]

## Next Steps
- [ ] [Step 1]
- [ ] [Step 2]

## Relevant Files
- [path/to/file1]
- [path/to/file2]

## Git References
- Issue: #[number] or [URL]
- Related commits: [commit hashes if any]
- Branch: [branch name]

---

*Generated by [YOUR_CODE_NAME] at [ISO_DATETIME]*
```
